            <prj:justificationText>We are requesting band 7 observations in full polarization mode, at the highest possible angular resolution.  Because of the large array of structure scales seen in the M87 jet, our science goal requires observations in both a fairly compact configuration (36-3) as well as in a high resolution configuration  (36-7).  This will yield observations at 0.04" angular resolution, 
comparable to the VLA in A array at 20 GHz, and nearly comparable to that of the HST. We intend to combine the data from the two array configurations in post-processing, a strategy that we have discussed at length with the US NRO.

This particular science goal is for the compact configuration (36-3) observations, which will yield ~0.3" resolution but will give us the ability to image the faint extended structures in the largest features in the jet (knots A and B, see Figure 2, right panels).  Band 7 is ideal for these observations as it has the smallest d-terms.  We will use the widest 2000 MHz bandwidth, and the TDM correlator, offering us the highest possible image fidelity.  

Because of the M87 jet's size (roughly 22 arcsec from end to end) and the fact that mosaic observations are not being offered in Cycle 3 in full polarization mode, both sets of observations will require 5 separate pointings (n.b., we are not asking to image the SW hotspot, which would require additional pointings).  These pointings are illustrated in Figure 1 (bottom right panel).

In each of the pointings, we will need to subtract out the emission in the other bands.  We have consulted with our NRO staff and they agree this is the best strategy for these observations.  This is something we have experience doing with the VLA, as due to its proximity M87 is one of the largest radio galaxies on the sky, with its lobes extending over 100 kpc (many arcminutes in angular extent) from the nucleus.  Our detailed spectral data on the M87 jet and nucleus, combined with existing images in both optical and radio, will give us the information we need to do this.  We will consult in detail with NRAO and ALMA staff about this process to ensure the highest possible final outcome.   </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The estimates we have used for the required RMS value are based on previous HST and VLA observations.  In most regions we expect the fluxes to fit on a power-law extending between those
two; however, it is likely that the detailed structure will be different than both of those bands.  The reasonability of these estimates can be seen by comparison to the existing, Cycle 1 ALMA observation of M87 in band 7, at much lower resolution (Vlahakis et al., Figure 1, top right panel).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
