    <prp:abstract>We propose ALMA imaging and polarimetry of the M87 jet in band 7 (0.87 mm wavelength).  Our team's detailed work on the M87 jet, extending over three decades, has found an intricate, knotty structure that can be seen from radio through X-rays, with the emission coming from synchrotron radiation.  High energy, optical and X-ray emitting electrons occupy only a fraction of the jet volume, physically distinct from the radio emitting particles, which are distributed throughout the jet.  Multi-band imaging polarimetry was critical to untangling this energetic structure and the field structure associated with it, as well as the physics relevant to the enormous flare of knot HST-1 a decade ago.  ALMA observations will open a new spectral window, intermediate between the radio and optical bands, helping us to bridge the gap between the two electron populations.  These data will have an angular resolution even better than HST and JVLA polarimetry and will yield exciting new information on the jet's energetic and magnetic field structure.  It will also serve as an important, quiescent-state reference epoch for a likely future flaring event.</prp:abstract>
